    <h1 class="article-header-h1">The IRMAA 2-Year Look-Back Trap: Why Your Medicare Premium in 2031 Is Based on What You Earn Today</h1>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="article-body-wrap">
  <p>There is a retirement planning mistake so common and so expensive that most people who make it never even realize they've made it. It happens in the final years before retirement — the years when income is highest, Roth conversions seem most urgent, and Medicare feels like a distant problem.</p>
  <p>The mistake is failing to understand the IRMAA look-back rule. For high-income pre-retirees, it can cost $15,000 or more in the first year of Medicare alone — and there's nothing you can do about it once that income year has closed.</p>

  <h2>What IRMAA actually is</h2>
  <p>IRMAA stands for Income-Related Monthly Adjustment Amount. It's a Medicare surcharge that increases your Part B and Part D premiums when your income exceeds certain thresholds. At the highest tier in 2026, IRMAA adds <strong>$15,976 per year per couple</strong> to Medicare costs — on top of the standard premium.</p>
  <div class="num-box">
    <div class="num-box-row"><span class="num-box-label">Standard Medicare Part B (2026, couple)</span><span class="num-box-val">$3,733/yr</span></div>
    <div class="num-box-row"><span class="num-box-label">Tier 1 IRMAA (MAGI $212k–$266k)</span><span class="num-box-val">+$5,909/yr</span></div>
    <div class="num-box-row"><span class="num-box-label">Tier 2 IRMAA (MAGI $266k–$334k)</span><span class="num-box-val">+$9,676/yr</span></div>
    <div class="num-box-row"><span class="num-box-label">Tier 3 IRMAA (MAGI $334k–$400k)</span><span class="num-box-val">+$12,805/yr</span></div>
    <div class="num-box-row"><span class="num-box-label">Tier 4 IRMAA (MAGI $400k–$750k)</span><span class="num-box-val hl">+$15,976/yr</span></div>
  </div>

  <h2>The look-back rule nobody mentions</h2>
  <p><strong>Medicare does not use your current year's income. It uses your income from two years prior.</strong></p>
  <p>This means your Medicare premium in 2031 is based on your 2029 tax return. If you're still earning a high salary in 2029, or doing large Roth conversions, that income determines your Medicare surcharge two years later — regardless of what your income is in 2031.</p>
  <div class="callout">
    <p><strong>The trap in plain numbers:</strong> You retire in 2026, earning $450,000. You start Medicare in 2031 (age 65). Your 2031 premium is based on your 2029 income — year 3 of retirement, when you may be converting $250,000+ from pre-tax IRA to Roth. That conversion plus other income could push MAGI above $400,000, landing you in Tier 4: $15,976 in extra Medicare premiums in 2031 alone.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>The planning window you actually have</h2>
  <p>This creates a very specific insight: <strong>to control your Medicare premiums in your first Medicare years, manage your income two years before Medicare starts — not in the Medicare years themselves.</strong></p>
  <p>For someone going on Medicare at 65, that means managing income at ages 63 and 64. The Roth conversion decisions you make at 63-64 have direct IRMAA consequences at 65-66. Yet most people optimize their conversions for the current-year tax bracket, completely ignoring the two-year Medicare shadow they're casting.</p>

  <h3>Strategy 1: Front-load conversions in years 59–62</h3>
  <p>These are your prime conversion years — no SS income, potentially lower overall income, and the IRMAA look-back doesn't yet reach your Medicare start date. A $250,000 conversion at age 61 does not affect your age 65 Medicare premium. A $250,000 conversion at age 63 does.</p>

  <h3>Strategy 2: Slow down in years 63–64</h3>
  <p>In the two years immediately before Medicare, convert only enough to stay below the tier threshold that matters most for your income level. For most high earners, that's keeping MAGI below $400,000 (Tier 4) or $334,000 (Tier 3). Run the numbers specifically — the difference between tiers is $3,000+ per year.</p>

  <h3>Strategy 3: File a Life Changing Event (LCE) appeal</h3>
  <p>If your income drops significantly the year you retire, you can appeal your IRMAA determination using Form SSA-44. Medicare will use your more recent income. If you retire mid-year with dramatically lower income, file this appeal immediately — it can eliminate the IRMAA surcharge in your first Medicare year.</p>

  <h3>Strategy 4: Use QCDs once eligible (age 70.5+)</h3>
  <p>Qualified Charitable Distributions reduce your AGI dollar-for-dollar. An $80,000 QCD in 2033 reduces your 2033 MAGI by $80,000 — which reduces your 2035 IRMAA tier. Given the $3,000–$6,000 per-tier cost difference, a well-timed QCD can pay for itself multiple times over.</p>

  <div class="tool-cta-block">
    <div>
      <h3>See your corrected IRMAA year by year</h3>
      <p>WealthVize calculates your IRMAA using the actual 2-year look-back across all 35 retirement years — not your current-year income. See exactly which years you're in which tier and how conversions affect it.</p>
    </div>
    <a href="../index.html#waitlist" class="btn-primary tool-cta-btn">Get Early Access →</a>
  </div>

  <h2>The key takeaway</h2>
  <p>IRMAA is not a retirement problem. It's a pre-retirement income problem that shows up two years later as a Medicare bill. Your highest-income working years — and your most aggressive Roth conversion years — cast a long shadow. The most important thing you can do is understand exactly which income years affect which Medicare years, then plan your conversion schedule around that map rather than your current-year bracket alone.</p>
  <p>The second most important thing: tell your advisor about this article and ask them to show you the IRMAA look-back in their projection. If they can't — or haven't thought about it — that's important information.</p>
</div>
